    "Liu et al. [116] proposed a Fourier transformbased encoding technique to assist the inverse design of diffractive optical elements.",
    "To make the binary structures compatible with frequency domain operations, they first transformed the binary images of the structures f e (x, y) into level set functions 𝜙 e (x, y), and then applied Fourier transform to the level set functions to encode the real-space information into the sparse momentum-space representations, while the decoding process was in a reverse order (see Figure 8(f)).",
    "With this topological encoding method, an eight-layer fully connected neural network was constructed to predict the transmission intensities of the nine diffraction channels for 3 × 3 diffractive beam splitters.",
    "Combined with this trained efficient simulator, they adopted a modified evolution strategy to globally search optimal structures that meet the required diffraction patterns (see Figure 8(g)).",
